Think about if the game launched in it's current state, but no one had ever seen or played the game before.  I think it'd be pretty damn successful. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=32662"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.nvbell.net/v1ector1/KareoTimeBanner.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#deddbf><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://p201.ezboard.com/btheconcerthall.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tamsindyresoul>Tamsin Dyresoul</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_magentaspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Minstrel</span><br>  Posts: 215<br> <font color=#330000>(9/4/04 8:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://p201.ezboard.com/ftheconcerthallbackstage.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=19747.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: oh man</span><hr size=1> I'd have to go with Kareo here.  I think even grumpy Liq would acknowledge the fun and exploration levels were so high back around Kunark era that we tended to overlook some of the nastier aspects such as binding issues, bard aggro(which was fixed later), and equipment issues (I'll summon some food and water now from my britches;b).<br>
<br>
I mean, LGuk used to be like a friday night club where we all met up with friends and aquaintences to hang out.<br>
<br>
When Kunark went live, I was on my necro.  My namesake here on EZboard.  I dropped my bard around level 23 late 1999, early 2000.  To be blunt, I just couldn't figure out how to play him since the aggro issues were so bad and I had read twisting guides on the old websites.  So I went Erudite necro and spent weeks in Tox forest.  No Paineel, no real bank unless you wanted to risk death in Erudin, etc.<br>
<br>
So I went through the FS dagger nerfs, pet nerfs, FD nerfs, and I'm pretty sure some resist rate nerfs in there as well.  Oh, and one of my favorite dungeons all time was Kunark:  Crypt of Dalnir.  Visceral Dagger quest was silly tough back in that time.<br>
<br>
As far to the future:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Now all said and done, the 'vision' spawned a fantastic game that's gone on longer than anyone expected. I'm not saying it's all bad. But for the people with the rose tinted lenses harking back on the vision...... I was hardly all good.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->  <br>
<br>
Liq, we are looking at the chicken and the egg here.  I propose the 'vision' made a game like EQ possible.  It separated the wheat from the chaff so to speak.  Yes, it was tough, and yes, it wasn't fair.  But it WAS engaging and addictive.  Challenging also comes to mind.  I think even a grumpy mod such as yourself might admit that there was some camp that you hated but once done, quietly boasted to friends and colleagues about completing.  Or perhaps it was some item.  Overall, that was what kept alot of us going.  Stick and carrot indeed.  But no need to knock a winning formula...lol.<br>
<br>
The real question is when does a game become too tedious?  And I think that will ulimately be answered by subscription rates.  If your like me, I gave alot of time to EQ, and I'm not looking to new games for a repeat performance.  However, younger folks that are new to the genre might be looking and or willing to dedicate that sorta time to a game.  We can't make that choice for them.  We have, however, been through that and are much less inclined to make the same choice again.  We look for games that are less demanding, less time-intensive, and don't require the massive amount of numbers to advance.  EQ is trying to appeal to us in that regard, EQ2 even moreso.  But we have been through the intensity that was EQ the first 3 or so years.  We know now what we want and what to avoid.  However we are still always looking for that feeling of 'newness' and 'exploration' in some new game.<br>
<br>
